[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] Thus the mean is an M-estimator of ρ-type, with this ρ function.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] As this ρ function is continuously differentiable in *θ*, the mean is thus also an M-estimator of ψ-type for ψ(*x*, *θ*) = *θ* − *x*.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] For the median estimation of (*X*1, ..., *X**n*), instead we can define the ρ function as $\rho (x,\theta )=|x-\theta |$ and similarly, the ρ function is minimized when *θ* is the median of the *X*s.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] M-estimators are consistent under various sets of conditions.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] A typical set of assumptions is the class of functions satisfies a uniform law of large numbers and that the maximum is well-separated.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] where $d:\Theta \times \Theta \rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ is a distance function and $\theta ^{*}$ is the optimum, then M-estimation is consistent.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] The uniform convergence constraint is not necessarily required; an alternate set of assumptions is to instead consider pointwise convergence (in probability) of the objective functions.
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] Additionally, assume that each of the $M_{n}$ has continuous derivative with exactly one zero or has a derivative which is non-decreasing and is asymptotically order $o_{p}(1)$ .
[src:robust-regression/m-estimator] Finally, assume that the maximum $\theta ^{*}$ is well-separated.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In statistics, an **outlier** is a data point that differs significantly from other observations.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] An outlier may be due to a variability in the measurement, an indication of novel data, or it may be the result of experimental error; the latter are sometimes excluded from the data set.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] An outlier can be an indication of exciting possibility, but can also cause serious problems in statistical analyses.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Outliers can occur by chance in any distribution, but they can indicate novel behaviour or structures in the data-set, measurement error, or that the population has a heavy-tailed distribution.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] A frequent cause of outliers is a mixture of two distributions, which may be two distinct sub-populations, or may indicate 'correct trial' versus 'measurement error'; this is modeled by a mixture model.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In most larger samplings of data, some data points will be further away from the sample mean than what is deemed reasonable.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] This can be due to incidental systematic error or flaws in the theory that generated an assumed family of probability distributions, or it may be that some observations are far from the center of the data.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Outlier points can therefore indicate faulty data, erroneous procedures, or areas where a certain theory might not be valid.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] However, in large samples, a small number of outliers is to be expected (and not due to any anomalous condition).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Outliers, being the most extreme observations, may include the sample maximum or sample minimum, or both, depending on whether they are extremely high or low.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] However, the sample maximum and minimum are not always outliers because they may not be unusually far from other observations.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Naive interpretation of statistics derived from data sets that include outliers may be misleading.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] For example, if one is calculating the average temperature of 10 objects in a room, and nine of them are between 20 and 25 degrees Celsius, but an oven is at 175 °C, the median of the data will be between 20 and 25 °C but the mean temperature will be between 35.5 and 40 °C.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In this case, the median better reflects the temperature of a randomly sampled object (but not the temperature in the room) than the mean; naively interpreting the mean as "a typical sample", equivalent to the median, is incorrect.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] As illustrated in this case, outliers may indicate data points that belong to a different population than the rest of the sample set.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Estimators capable of coping with outliers are said to be robust: the median is a robust statistic of central tendency, while the mean is not.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In the case of normally distributed data, the three sigma rule means that roughly 1 in 22 observations will differ by twice the standard deviation or more from the mean, and 1 in 370 will deviate by three times the standard deviation.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] If the sample size is only 100, however, just three such outliers are already reason for concern, being more than 11 times the expected number.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Thus if one takes a normal distribution with cutoff 3 standard deviations from the mean, *p* is approximately 0.3%, and thus for 1000 trials one can approximate the number of samples whose deviation exceeds 3 sigmas by a Poisson distribution with λ = 3.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Outliers can have many anomalous causes.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] A physical apparatus for taking measurements may have suffered a transient malfunction.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] There may have been an error in data transmission or transcription.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Outliers arise due to changes in system behaviour, fraudulent behaviour, human error, instrument error or simply through natural deviations in populations.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] A sample may have been contaminated with elements from outside the population being examined.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Alternatively, an outlier could be the result of a flaw in the assumed theory, calling for further investigation by the researcher.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Additionally, the pathological appearance of outliers of a certain form appears in a variety of datasets, indicating that the causative mechanism for the data might differ at the extreme end (King effect).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] There is no rigid mathematical definition of what constitutes an outlier; determining whether or not an observation is an outlier is ultimately a subjective exercise.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] There are various methods of outlier detection, some of which are treated as synonymous with novelty detection.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Some are graphical such as normal probability plots.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Other methods flag observations based on measures such as the interquartile range.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] John Tukey proposed this test, where $k=1.5$ indicates an "outlier", and $k=3$ indicates data that is "far out".
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In various domains such as, but not limited to, statistics, signal processing, finance, econometrics, manufacturing, networking and data mining, the task of *anomaly detection* may take other approaches.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Some of these may be distance-based and density-based such as Local Outlier Factor (LOF).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Some approaches may use the distance to the k-nearest neighbors to label observations as outliers or non-outliers.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The modified Thompson Tau test is a method used to determine if an outlier exists in a data set.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The strength of this method lies in the fact that it takes into account a data set's standard deviation, average and provides a statistically determined rejection zone; thus providing an objective method to determine if a data point is an outlier.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] How it works: First, a data set's average is determined.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Next the absolute deviation between each data point and the average are determined.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] where $\scriptstyle {t_{\alpha /2}}$ is the critical value from the Student t distribution with *n*-2 degrees of freedom, *n* is the sample size, and s is the sample standard deviation.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] To determine if a value is an outlier: Calculate $\scriptstyle \delta =|(X-mean(X))/s|$ .
[src:robust-regression/outlier] If *δ* > Rejection Region, the data point is an outlier.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] If *δ* ≤ Rejection Region, the data point is not an outlier.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The modified Thompson Tau test is used to find one outlier at a time (largest value of *δ* is removed if it is an outlier).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Meaning, if a data point is found to be an outlier, it is removed from the data set and the test is applied again with a new average and rejection region.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] This process is continued until no outliers remain in a data set.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Some work has also examined outliers for nominal (or categorical) data.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In the context of a set of examples (or instances) in a data set, instance hardness measures the probability that an instance will be misclassified ( $1-p(y|x)$ where y is the assigned class label and x represent the input attribute value for an instance in the training set t).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Practically, this formulation is unfeasible as H is potentially infinite and calculating $p(h|t)$ is unknown for many algorithms.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] where $g_{j}(t,\alpha )$ is the hypothesis induced by learning algorithm $g_{j}$ trained on training set t with hyperparameters $\alpha$ .
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Instance hardness provides a continuous value for determining if an instance is an outlier instance.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The choice of how to deal with an outlier should depend on the cause.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Some estimators are highly sensitive to outliers, notably estimation of covariance matrices.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Even when a normal distribution model is appropriate to the data being analyzed, outliers are expected for large sample sizes and should not automatically be discarded if that is the case.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Instead, one should use a method that is robust to outliers to model or analyze data with naturally occurring outliers.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] When deciding whether to remove an outlier, the cause has to be considered.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] As mentioned earlier, if the outlier's origin can be attributed to an experimental error, or if it can be otherwise determined that the outlying data point is erroneous, it is generally recommended to remove it.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] However, it is more desirable to correct the erroneous value, if possible.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Removing a data point solely because it is an outlier, on the other hand, is a controversial practice, often frowned upon by many scientists and science instructors, as it typically invalidates statistical results.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] While mathematical criteria provide an objective and quantitative method for data rejection, they do not make the practice more scientifically or methodologically sound, especially in small sets or where a normal distribution cannot be assumed.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Rejection of outliers is more acceptable in areas of practice where the underlying model of the process being measured and the usual distribution of measurement error are confidently known.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The two common approaches to exclude outliers are truncation (or trimming) and Winsorising.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Trimming discards the outliers whereas Winsorising replaces the outliers with the nearest "nonsuspect" data.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Exclusion can also be a consequence of the measurement process, such as when an experiment is not entirely capable of measuring such extreme values, resulting in censored data.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In regression problems, an alternative approach may be to only exclude points which exhibit a large degree of influence on the estimated coefficients, using a measure such as Cook's distance.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] If a data point (or points) is excluded from the data analysis, this should be clearly stated on any subsequent report.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] The possibility should be considered that the underlying distribution of the data is not approximately normal, having "fat tails".
[src:robust-regression/outlier] For instance, when sampling from a Cauchy distribution, the sample variance increases with the sample size, the sample mean fails to converge as the sample size increases, and outliers are expected at far larger rates than for a normal distribution.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Even a slight difference in the fatness of the tails can make a large difference in the expected number of extreme values.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] A set membership approach considers that the uncertainty corresponding to the *i*th measurement of an unknown random vector *x* is represented by a set *X*i (instead of a probability density function).
[src:robust-regression/outlier] If no outliers occur, *x* should belong to the intersection of all *X*i's.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] When outliers occur, this intersection could be empty, and we should relax a small number of the sets *X*i (as small as possible) in order to avoid any inconsistency.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] This can be done using the notion of *q*-relaxed intersection.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] As illustrated by the figure, the *q*-relaxed intersection corresponds to the set of all *x* which belong to all sets except *q* of them.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Sets *X*i that do not intersect the *q*-relaxed intersection could be suspected to be outliers.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In cases where the cause of the outliers is known, it may be possible to incorporate this effect into the model structure, for example by using a hierarchical Bayes model, or a mixture model.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] In cluster analysis, outliers can greatly distort the results.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Thus, the handling of outliers has been an issue of much discussion.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] Cluster analysis relies heavily on distance measures.
[src:robust-regression/outlier] It has been suggested that Manhattan distance, due to the lack of squaring disproportionately large difference values, is likely to handle outliers better than Euclidean distance.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In robust statistics, **robust regression** seeks to overcome some limitations of traditional regression analysis.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] A regression analysis models the relationship between one or more independent variables and a dependent variable.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Standard types of regression, such as ordinary least squares, have favourable properties if their underlying assumptions are true, but can give misleading results otherwise (i.e. are not robust to assumption violations).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Robust regression methods are designed to limit the effect that violations of assumptions by the underlying data-generating process have on regression estimates.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] For example, least squares estimates for regression models are highly sensitive to outliers: an outlier with twice the error magnitude of a typical observation contributes four (two squared) times as much to the squared error loss, and therefore has more leverage over the regression estimates.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The Huber loss function is a robust alternative to standard square error loss that reduces outliers' contributions to the squared error loss, thereby limiting their impact on regression estimates.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] One instance in which robust estimation should be considered is when there is a strong suspicion of heteroscedasticity.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In the homoscedastic model, it is assumed that the variance of the error term is constant for all values of *x*.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Heteroscedasticity allows the variance to be dependent on *x*, which is more accurate for many real scenarios.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] For example, the variance of expenditure is often larger for individuals with higher income than for individuals with lower incomes.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Software packages usually default to a homoscedastic model, even though such a model may be less accurate than a heteroscedastic model.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] One simple approach (Tofallis, 2008) is to apply least squares to percentage errors, as this reduces the influence of the larger values of the dependent variable compared to ordinary least squares.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another common situation in which robust estimation is used occurs when the data contain outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In the presence of outliers that do not come from the same data-generating process as the rest of the data, least squares estimation is inefficient and can be biased.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Because the least squares predictions are dragged towards the outliers, and because the variance of the estimates is artificially inflated, the result is that outliers can be masked.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Although it is sometimes claimed that least squares (or classical statistical methods in general) are robust, they are only robust in the sense that the type I error rate does not increase under violations of the model.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In fact, the type I error rate tends to be lower than the nominal level when outliers are present, and there is often a dramatic increase in the type II error rate.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The reduction of the type I error rate has been labelled as the *conservatism* of classical methods.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Despite their superior performance over least squares estimation in many situations, robust methods for regression are still not widely used.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Several reasons may help explain their unpopularity (Hampel et al.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] One possible reason is that there are several competing methods and the field got off to many false starts.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Also, robust estimates are much more computationally intensive than least squares estimation; in recent years, however, this objection has become less relevant, as computing power has increased greatly.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another reason may be that some popular statistical software packages failed to implement the methods (Stromberg, 2004).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Also, modern statistical software packages such as R, SAS, Statsmodels, Stata and S-PLUS include considerable functionality for robust estimation (see, for example, the books by Venables and Ripley, and by Maronna et al.).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The simplest methods of estimating parameters in a regression model that are less sensitive to outliers than the least squares estimates, is to use least absolute deviations.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Even then, gross outliers can still have a considerable impact on the model, motivating research into even more robust approaches.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In 1964, Huber introduced M-estimation for regression.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The M in M-estimation stands for "maximum likelihood type".
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The method is robust to outliers in the response variable, but turned out not to be resistant to outliers in the explanatory variables (leverage points).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In fact, when there are outliers in the explanatory variables, the method has no advantage over least squares.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] In the 1980s, several alternatives to M-estimation were proposed as attempts to overcome the lack of resistance.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] See the book by Rousseeuw and Leroy for a very practical review.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Least trimmed squares (LTS) is a viable alternative and is currently (2007) the preferred choice of Rousseeuw and Ryan (1997, 2008).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The Theil–Sen estimator has a lower breakdown point than LTS but is statistically efficient and popular.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another proposed solution was S-estimation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] This method finds a line (plane or hyperplane) that minimizes a robust estimate of the scale (from which the method gets the S in its name) of the residuals.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] This method is highly resistant to leverage points and is robust to outliers in the response.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] However, this method was also found to be inefficient.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] MM-estimation attempts to retain the robustness and resistance of S-estimation, whilst gaining the efficiency of M-estimation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The method proceeds by finding a highly robust and resistant S-estimate that minimizes an M-estimate of the scale of the residuals (the first M in the method's name).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The estimated scale is then held constant whilst a close by M-estimate of the parameters is located (the second M).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another approach to robust estimation of regression models is to replace the normal distribution with a heavy-tailed distribution.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] A *t*-distribution with 4–6 degrees of freedom has been reported to be a good choice in various practical situations.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Bayesian robust regression, being fully parametric, relies heavily on such distributions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Under the assumption of *t*-distributed residuals, the distribution is a location-scale family.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] That is, $x\leftarrow (x-\mu )/\sigma$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The degrees of freedom of the *t*-distribution is sometimes called the *kurtosis parameter*.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Lange, Little and Taylor (1989) discuss this model in some depth from a non-Bayesian point of view.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] A Bayesian account appears in Gelman et al.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] An alternative parametric approach is to assume that the residuals follow a mixture of normal distributions (Daemi et al.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] 2019); in particular, a **contaminated normal distribution** in which the majority of observations are from a specified normal distribution, but a small proportion are from a normal distribution with much higher variance.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] This is sometimes called the $\varepsilon$ -contamination model.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Parametric approaches have the advantage that likelihood theory provides an "off-the-shelf" approach to inference (although for mixture models such as the $\varepsilon$ -contamination model, the usual regularity conditions might not apply), and it is possible to build simulation models from the fit.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] However, such parametric models still assume that the underlying model is literally true.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] As such, they do not account for skewed residual distributions or finite observation precisions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another robust method is the use of unit weights (Wainer & Thissen, 1976), a method that can be applied when there are multiple predictors of a single outcome.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Ernest Burgess (1928) used unit weights to predict success on parole.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] He scored 21 positive factors as present (e.g., "no prior arrest" = 1) or absent ("prior arrest" = 0), then summed to yield a predictor score, which was shown to be a useful predictor of parole success.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Wilks (1938) showed that nearly all sets of regression weights sum to composites that are very highly correlated with one another, including unit weights, a result sometimes referred to as Wilks' theorem (Ree, Carretta, & Earles, 1998).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Robyn Dawes (1979) examined decision making in applied settings, showing that simple models with unit weights often outperformed human experts.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Bobko, Roth, and Buster (2007) reviewed the literature on unit weights and concluded that decades of empirical studies show that unit weights perform similar to ordinary regression weights on cross validation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The BUPA liver data have been studied by various authors, including Breiman (2001).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The data can be found at the classic data sets page, and there is some discussion in the article on the Box–Cox transformation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] A plot of the logs of ALT versus the logs of γGT appears below.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The two regression lines are those estimated by ordinary least squares (OLS) and by robust MM-estimation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The analysis was performed in R using software made available by Venables and Ripley (2002).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The two regression lines appear to be very similar (and this is not unusual in a data set of this size).
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] However, the advantage of the robust approach comes to light when the estimates of residual scale are considered.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] For ordinary least squares, the estimate of scale is 0.420, compared to 0.373 for the robust method.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Thus, the relative efficiency of ordinary least squares to MM-estimation in this example is 1.266.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] This inefficiency leads to loss of power in hypothesis tests and to unnecessarily wide confidence intervals on estimated parameters.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Another consequence of the inefficiency of the ordinary least squares fit is that several outliers are masked because the estimate of residual scale is inflated; the scaled residuals are pushed closer to zero than when a more appropriate estimate of scale is used.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The plots of the scaled residuals from the two models appear below.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The variable on the *x* axis is just the observation number as it appeared in the data set.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Rousseeuw and Leroy (1986) contains many such plots.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] The horizontal reference lines are at 2 and −2, so that any observed scaled residual beyond these boundaries can be considered to be an outlier.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Clearly, the least squares method leads to many interesting observations being masked.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Whilst in one or two dimensions outlier detection using classical methods can be performed manually, with large data sets and in high dimensions the problem of masking can make identification of many outliers impossible.
[src:robust-regression/robust-regression] Robust methods automatically detect these observations, offering a serious advantage over classical methods when outliers are present.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Robust statistics seek to provide methods that emulate popular statistical methods, but are not unduly affected by outliers or other small departures from model assumptions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In statistics, classical estimation methods rely heavily on assumptions that are often not met in practice.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In particular, it is often assumed that the data errors are normally distributed, at least approximately, or that the central limit theorem can be relied on to produce normally distributed estimates.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Unfortunately, when there are outliers in the data, classical estimators often have very poor performance, when judged using the *breakdown point* and the *influence function* described below.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The practical effect of problems seen in the influence function can be studied empirically by examining the sampling distribution of proposed estimators under a mixture model, where one mixes in a small amount (1–5% is often sufficient) of contamination.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For instance, one may use a mixture of 95% a normal distribution, and 5% a normal distribution with the same mean but significantly higher standard deviation (representing outliers).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] There are various definitions of a "robust statistic".
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Strictly speaking, a **robust statistic** is resistant to errors in the results, produced by deviations from assumptions (e.g., of normality).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This means that if the assumptions are only approximately met, the **robust estimator** will still have a reasonable efficiency, and reasonably small bias, as well as being asymptotically unbiased, meaning having a bias tending towards 0 as the sample size tends towards infinity.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Usually, the most important case is **distributional robustness** - robustness to breaking of the assumptions about the underlying distribution of the data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Classical statistical procedures are typically sensitive to "longtailedness" (e.g., when the distribution of the data has longer tails than the assumed normal distribution).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This implies that they will be strongly affected by the presence of outliers in the data, and the estimates they produce may be heavily distorted if there are extreme outliers in the data, compared to what they would be if the outliers were not included in the data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] By contrast, more robust estimators that are not so sensitive to distributional distortions such as longtailedness are also resistant to the presence of outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Thus, in the context of robust statistics, *distributionally robust* and *outlier-resistant* are effectively synonymous.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For one perspective on research in robust statistics up to 2000, see Portnoy & He (2000).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Some experts prefer the term **resistant statistics** for distributional robustness, and reserve 'robustness' for non-distributional robustness, e.g., robustness to violation of assumptions about the probability model or estimator, but this is a minority usage.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Plain 'robustness' to mean 'distributional robustness' is common.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The mean is not a robust measure of central tendency.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] If the dataset is, e.g., the values {2,3,5,6,9}, then if we add another datapoint with value -1000 or +1000 to the data, the resulting mean will be very different from the mean of the original data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Similarly, if we replace one of the values with a datapoint of value -1000 or +1000 then the resulting mean will be very different from the mean of the original data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The median is a robust measure of central tendency.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Taking the same dataset {2,3,5,6,9}, if we add another datapoint with value -1000 or +1000 then the median will change slightly, but it will still be similar to the median of the original data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] If we replace one of the values with a data point of value -1000 or +1000 then the resulting median will still be similar to the median of the original data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Described in terms of breakdown points, the median has a breakdown point of 50%, meaning that half the points must be outliers before the median can be moved outside the range of the non-outliers, while the mean has a breakdown point of 0, as a single large observation can throw it off.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The median absolute deviation and interquartile range are robust measures of statistical dispersion, while the standard deviation and range are not.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Trimmed estimators and Winsorised estimators are general methods to make statistics more robust.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] L-estimators are a general class of simple statistics, often robust, while M-estimators are a general class of robust statistics, and are now the preferred solution, though they can be quite involved to calculate.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Gelman et al. in Bayesian Data Analysis (2004) consider a data set relating to speed-of-light measurements made by Simon Newcomb.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The data sets for that book can be found via the Classic data sets page, and the book's website contains more information on the data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Although the bulk of the data looks to be more or less normally distributed, there are two obvious outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] These outliers have a large effect on the mean, dragging it towards them, and away from the center of the bulk of the data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Thus, if the mean is intended as a measure of the location of the center of the data, it is, in a sense, biased when outliers are present.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Also, the distribution of the mean is known to be asymptotically normal due to the central limit theorem.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, outliers can make the distribution of the mean non-normal, even for fairly large data sets.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Besides this non-normality, the mean is also inefficient in the presence of outliers and less variable measures of location are available.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The plot below shows a density plot of the speed-of-light data, together with a rug plot (panel (a)).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Also shown is a normal Q–Q plot (panel (b)).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The outliers are visible in these plots.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Panels (c) and (d) of the plot show the bootstrap distribution of the mean (c) and the 10% trimmed mean (d).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The trimmed mean is a simple, robust estimator of location that deletes a certain percentage of observations (10% here) *from each end* of the data, then computes the mean in the usual way.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The analysis was performed in R and 10,000 bootstrap samples were used for each of the raw and trimmed means.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The distribution of the mean is clearly much wider than that of the 10% trimmed mean (the plots are on the same scale).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Also whereas the distribution of the trimmed mean appears to be close to normal, the distribution of the raw mean is quite skewed to the left.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] So, in this sample of 66 observations, only 2 outliers cause the central limit theorem to be inapplicable.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Robust statistical methods, of which the trimmed mean is a simple example, seek to outperform classical statistical methods in the presence of outliers, or, more generally, when underlying parametric assumptions are not quite correct.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Whilst the trimmed mean performs well relative to the mean in this example, better robust estimates are available.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In fact, the mean, median and trimmed mean are all special cases of M-estimators.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The plots below show the bootstrap distributions of the standard deviation, the median absolute deviation (MAD) and the Rousseeuw–Croux (Qn) estimator of scale.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The plots are based on 10,000 bootstrap samples for each estimator, with some Gaussian noise added to the resampled data (smoothed bootstrap).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Panel (a) shows the distribution of the standard deviation, (b) of the MAD and (c) of Qn.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The distribution of standard deviation is erratic and wide, a result of the outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The MAD is better behaved, and Qn is a little bit more efficient than MAD.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This simple example demonstrates that when outliers are present, the standard deviation cannot be recommended as an estimate of scale.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Traditionally, statisticians would manually screen data for outliers, and remove them, usually checking the source of the data to see whether the outliers were erroneously recorded.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Indeed, in the speed-of-light example above, it is easy to see and remove the two outliers prior to proceeding with any further analysis.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, in modern times, data sets often consist of large numbers of variables being measured on large numbers of experimental units.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Therefore, manual screening for outliers is often impractical.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Outliers can often interact in such a way that they mask each other.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] As a simple example, consider a small univariate data set containing one modest and one large outlier.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The estimated standard deviation will be grossly inflated by the large outlier.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The result is that the modest outlier looks relatively normal.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] As soon as the large outlier is removed, the estimated standard deviation shrinks, and the modest outlier now looks unusual.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This problem of masking gets worse as the complexity of the data increases.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For example, in regression problems, diagnostic plots are used to identify outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, it is common that once a few outliers have been removed, others become visible.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The problem is even worse in higher dimensions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Robust methods provide automatic ways of detecting, downweighting (or removing), and flagging outliers, largely removing the need for manual screening.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Care must be taken; initial data showing the ozone hole first appearing over Antarctica were rejected as outliers by non-human screening.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Although this article deals with general principles for univariate statistical methods, robust methods also exist for regression problems, generalized linear models, and parameter estimation of various distributions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The basic tools used to describe and measure robustness are the *breakdown point*, the *influence function* and the *sensitivity curve*.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Intuitively, the breakdown point of an estimator is the proportion of incorrect observations (e.g. arbitrarily large observations) an estimator can handle before giving an incorrect (e.g., arbitrarily large) result.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Usually, the asymptotic (infinite sample) limit is quoted as the breakdown point, although the finite-sample breakdown point may be more useful.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For example, given n independent random variables $(X_{1},\dots ,X_{n})$ and the corresponding realizations $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , we can use ${\overline {X_{n}}}:={\frac {X_{1}+\cdots +X_{n}}{n}}$ to estimate the mean.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Such an estimator has a breakdown point of 0 (or finite-sample breakdown point of $1/n$ ) because we can make ${\overline {x}}$ arbitrarily large just by changing any of $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The higher the breakdown point of an estimator, the more robust it is.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Intuitively, we can understand that a breakdown point cannot exceed 50% because if more than half of the observations are contaminated, it is not possible to distinguish between the underlying distribution and the contaminating distribution Rousseeuw & Leroy (1987).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Therefore, the maximum breakdown point is 0.5 and there are estimators which achieve such a breakdown point.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For example, the median has a breakdown point of 0.5.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The X% trimmed mean has a breakdown point of X%, for the chosen level of X.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The level and the power breakdown points of tests are investigated in He, Simpson & Portnoy (1990).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In the speed-of-light example, removing the two lowest observations causes the mean to change from 26.2 to 27.75, a change of 1.55.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The estimate of scale produced by the Qn method is 6.3.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] We can divide this by the square root of the sample size to get a robust standard error, and we find this quantity to be 0.78.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Thus, the change in the mean resulting from removing two outliers is approximately twice the robust standard error.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The 10% trimmed mean for the speed-of-light data is 27.43.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Removing the two lowest observations and recomputing gives 27.67.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The trimmed mean is less affected by the outliers and has a higher breakdown point.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] If we replace the lowest observation, −44, by −1000, the mean becomes 11.73, whereas the 10% trimmed mean is still 27.43.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In many areas of applied statistics, it is common for data to be log-transformed to make them near symmetrical.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Very small values become large negative when log-transformed, and zeroes become negatively infinite.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Therefore, this example is of practical interest.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The empirical influence function is a measure of the dependence of the estimator on the value of any one of the points in the sample.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] It is a model-free measure in the sense that it simply relies on calculating the estimator again with a different sample.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] On the right is Tukey's biweight function, which, as we will later see, is an example of what a "good" (in a sense defined later on) empirical influence function should look like.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The empirical influence function is defined as follows.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] What this means is that we are replacing the *i*-th value in the sample by an arbitrary value and looking at the output of the estimator.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Alternatively, the EIF is defined as the effect, scaled by n+1 instead of n, on the estimator of adding the point x to the sample.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Instead of relying solely on the data, we could use the distribution of the random variables.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The approach is quite different from that of the previous paragraph.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] What we are now trying to do is to see what happens to an estimator when we change the distribution of the data slightly: it assumes a *distribution,* and measures sensitivity to change in this distribution.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] By contrast, the empirical influence assumes a *sample set,* and measures sensitivity to change in the samples.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Let A be a convex subset of the set of all finite signed measures on $\Sigma$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] We want to estimate the parameter $\theta \in \Theta$ of a distribution F in A .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Let the functional $T:A\to \Gamma$ be the asymptotic value of some estimator sequence $(T_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] We will suppose that this functional is Fisher consistent, i.e. $\forall \theta \in \Theta ,T(F_{\theta })=\theta$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This means that at the model F , the estimator sequence asymptotically measures the correct quantity.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] What happens when the data doesn't follow the model F exactly but another, slightly different, "going towards" G ?
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] which is the one-sided Gateaux derivative of T at F , in the direction of $G-F$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Let $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ . $\Delta _{x}$ is the probability measure which gives mass 1 to $\{x\}$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] It describes the effect of an infinitesimal contamination at the point x on the estimate we are seeking, standardized by the mass t of the contamination (the asymptotic bias caused by contamination in the observations).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For a robust estimator, we want a bounded influence function, that is, one which does not go to infinity as x becomes arbitrarily large.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The empirical influence function uses the empirical distribution function ${\hat {F}}$ instead of the distribution function F , making use of the drop-in principle.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Small local-shift sensitivity $\lambda ^{*}$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This value, which looks a lot like a Lipschitz constant, represents the effect of shifting an observation slightly from x to a neighbouring point y , i.e., add an observation at y and remove one at x .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Historically, several approaches to robust estimation were proposed, including R-estimators and L-estimators.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, M-estimators now appear to dominate the field as a result of their generality, their potential for high breakdown points and comparatively high efficiency.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, they can be designed to achieve favourable properties, including robustness.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] M-estimator are a generalization of maximum likelihood estimators (MLEs) which is determined by maximizing ${\textstyle \prod _{i=1}^{n}f(x_{i})}$ or, equivalently, minimizing ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}-\log f(x_{i})}$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In 1964, Huber proposed to generalize this to the minimization of ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{n}\rho (x_{i})}$ , where $\rho$ is some function.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] MLE are therefore a special case of M-estimators (hence the name: "*M*aximum likelihood type" estimators).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Several choices of $\rho$ and $\psi$ have been proposed.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The two figures below show four $\rho$ functions and their corresponding $\psi$ functions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For squared errors, $\rho (x)$ increases at an accelerating rate, whilst for absolute errors, it increases at a constant rate.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] When Winsorizing is used, a mixture of these two effects is introduced: for small values of x, $\rho$ increases at the squared rate, but once the chosen threshold is reached (1.5 in this example), the rate of increase becomes constant.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] This Winsorised estimator is also known as the Huber loss function.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Tukey's biweight (also known as bisquare) function behaves in a similar way to the squared error function at first, but for larger errors, the function tapers off.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] M-estimators do not necessarily relate to a probability density function.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Therefore, off-the-shelf approaches to inference that arise from likelihood theory can not, in general, be used.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] It can be shown that M-estimators are asymptotically normally distributed so that as long as their standard errors can be computed, an approximate approach to inference is available.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Since M-estimators are normal only asymptotically, for small sample sizes it might be appropriate to use an alternative approach to inference, such as the bootstrap.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, M-estimates are not necessarily unique (i.e., there might be more than one solution that satisfies the equations).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Also, it is possible that any particular bootstrap sample can contain more outliers than the estimator's breakdown point.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Therefore, some care is needed when designing bootstrap schemes.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Of course, as we saw with the speed-of-light example, the mean is only normally distributed asymptotically and when outliers are present the approximation can be very poor even for quite large samples.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, classical statistical tests, including those based on the mean, are typically bounded above by the nominal size of the test.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The same is not true of M-estimators and the type I error rate can be substantially above the nominal level.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] These considerations do not "invalidate" M-estimation in any way.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] They merely make clear that some care is needed in their use, as is true of any other method of estimation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] It can be shown that the influence function of an M-estimator T is proportional to $\psi$ , which means we can derive the properties of such an estimator (such as its rejection point, gross-error sensitivity or local-shift sensitivity) when we know its $\psi$ function.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In many practical situations, the choice of the $\psi$ function is not critical to gaining a good robust estimate, and many choices will give similar results that offer great improvements, in terms of efficiency and bias, over classical estimates in the presence of outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Theoretically, $\psi$ functions are to be preferred, and Tukey's biweight (also known as bisquare) function is a popular choice.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Maronna et al. recommend the biweight function with efficiency at the normal set to 85%.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] M-estimators do not necessarily relate to a density function and so are not fully parametric.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Fully parametric approaches to robust modeling and inference, both Bayesian and likelihood approaches, usually deal with heavy-tailed distributions such as Student's *t*-distribution.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] For $\nu =1$ , the *t*-distribution is equivalent to the Cauchy distribution.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The degrees of freedom is sometimes known as the *kurtosis parameter*.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] It is the parameter that controls how heavy the tails are.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In principle, $\nu$ can be estimated from the data in the same way as any other parameter.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In practice, it is common for there to be multiple local maxima when $\nu$ is allowed to vary.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] As such, it is common to fix $\nu$ at a value around 4 or 6.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The figure below displays the $\psi$ -function for 4 different values of $\nu$ .
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] A pivotal quantity is a function of data, whose underlying population distribution is a member of a parametric family, that is not dependent on the values of the parameters.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] An ancillary statistic is such a function that is also a statistic, meaning that it is computed in terms of the data alone.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Thus test statistics, frequently constructed in terms of these to not be sensitive to assumptions about parameters, are still very sensitive to model assumptions.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Replacing missing data is called imputation.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] If there are relatively few missing points, there are some models which can be used to estimate values to complete the series, such as replacing missing values with the mean or median of the data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Simple linear regression can also be used to estimate missing values.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In addition, outliers can sometimes be accommodated in the data through the use of trimmed means, other scale estimators apart from standard deviation (e.g., MAD) and Winsorization.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In calculations of a trimmed mean, a fixed percentage of data is dropped from each end of an ordered data, thus eliminating the outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The mean is then calculated using the remaining data.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Winsorizing involves accommodating an outlier by replacing it with the next highest or next smallest value as appropriate.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] However, using these types of models to predict missing values or outliers in a long time series is difficult and often unreliable, particularly if the number of values to be in-filled is relatively high in comparison with total record length.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The accuracy of the estimate depends on how good and representative the model is and how long the period of missing values extends.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] When dynamic evolution is assumed in a series, the missing data point problem becomes an exercise in multivariate analysis (rather than the univariate approach of most traditional methods of estimating missing values and outliers).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] In such cases, a multivariate model will be more representative than a univariate one for predicting missing values.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] The Kohonen self organising map (KSOM) offers a simple and robust multivariate model for data analysis, thus providing good possibilities to estimate missing values, taking into account their relationship or correlation with other pertinent variables in the data record.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Standard Kalman filters are not robust to outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] To this end Ting, Theodorou & Schaal (2007) have recently shown that a modification of Masreliez's theorem can deal with outliers.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] One common approach to handle outliers in data analysis is to perform outlier detection first, followed by an efficient estimation method (e.g., the least squares).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] While this approach is often useful, one must keep in mind two challenges.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] First, an outlier detection method that relies on a non-robust initial fit can suffer from the effect of masking, that is, a group of outliers can mask each other and escape detection.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Second, if a high breakdown initial fit is used for outlier detection, the follow-up analysis might inherit some of the inefficiencies of the initial estimator.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Although influence functions have a long history in statistics, they were not widely used in machine learning due to several challenges.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] One of the primary obstacles is that traditional influence functions rely on expensive second-order derivative computations and assume model differentiability and convexity.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] These assumptions are limiting, especially in modern machine learning, where models are often non-differentiable, non-convex, and operate in high-dimensional spaces.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Koh & Liang (2017) addressed these challenges by introducing methods to efficiently approximate influence functions using second-order optimization techniques, such as those developed by Pearlmutter (1994), Martens (2010), and Agarwal, Bullins & Hazan (2017).
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Their approach remains effective even when the assumptions of differentiability and convexity degrade, enabling influence functions to be used in the context of non-convex deep learning models.
[src:robust-regression/robust-statistics] Koh and Liang’s contributions have opened the door for influence functions to be used in various applications across machine learning, from interpretability to security, marking a significant advance in their applicability.
